SIMPLE: miser
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Miser
<hw>Mi"ser</hw> <pr>(m⟦imac⟧"z⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>miser</ets> wretched, miserable; cf. Gr. <grk>mi^sos</grk> hate,
<grk>misei^n</grk> to hate: cf. It. & Sp. <ets>misero</ets> wretched,
avaricious.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A wretched person; a person afflicted by any great
misfortune.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The woeful words of a <qex>miser</qex> now despairing.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A despicable person; a wretch.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A covetous, grasping, mean person; esp., one having
wealth, who lives miserably for the sake of saving and increasing his
hoard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As some lone <qex>miser</qex>, visiting his store,⟦br⟧
Bends at his treasure, counts, recounts it o'er.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A stingy person; one very reluctant to spend
money.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A kind of large earth auger.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Miserable</ent>⟦br⟧
